otland":"Skotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Skotland","of Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1397–July 1459":"1397–juli 1459","1379–1483":"1379–1483","1435–1488":"1435–1488","1435–1502":"1435–1502","1440–Male":"1440–Overleden","1441–1478":"1441–1478","1442–Male":"1442–Overleden","1397–1459":"1397–1459","1440":"1440","July 1459":"juli 1459","1483":"1483","1459":"1459","Jul. 1459":"juli 1459","1502":"1502","1435":"1435","abt 1435":"circa 1435","1478":"1478","1379":"1379","1488":"1488","about 1435":"circa 1435","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","1441":"1441","about 1442":"circa 1442","about 1440":"circa 1440","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Closeburn, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Schotland","Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Schotland","of Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1397–July 1459":"1397–July 1459","1379–1483":"1379–1483","1435–1488":"1435–1488","1435–1502":"1435–1502","1440–Male":"1440–Deceased","1441–1478":"1441–1478","1442–Male":"1442–Deceased","1397–1459":"1397–1459","1440":"1440","July 1459":"July 1459","1483":"1483","1459":"1459","Jul. 1459":"July 1459","1502":"1502","1435":"1435","abt 1435":"about 1435","1478":"1478","1379":"1379","1488":"1488","about 1435":"about 1435","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","1441":"1441","about 1442":"about 1442","about 1440":"about 1440","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Closeburn, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland","of Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Somerville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Graveron-Sémerville in Eure (Normandy), from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigimar</i> (see   Siemer  ) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Somerville was born in 1397, in Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland. She married Ivan Thomas de Kirkpatrick in 1435, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in July 1459, in Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, at the age of 62, and was buried in Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1397–July 1459":"1397–juuli 1459","1379–1483":"1379–1483","1435–1488":"1435–1488","1435–1502":"1435–1502","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1441–1478":"1441–1478","1442–Male":"1442–Surnud","1397–1459":"1397–1459","1440":"1440","July 1459":"juuli 1459","1483":"1483","1459":"1459","Jul. 1459":"juuli 1459","1502":"1502","1435":"1435","abt 1435":"umbes 1435","1478":"1478","1379":"1379","1488":"1488","about 1435":"umbes 1435","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","1441":"1441","about 1442":"umbes 1442","about 1440":"umbes 1440","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Closeburn, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland","of Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1397–July 1459":"1397–heinäkuu 1459","1379–1483":"1379–1483","1435–1488":"1435–1488","1435–1502":"1435–1502","1440–Male":"1440–Kuollut","1441–1478":"1441–1478","1442–Male":"1442–Kuollut","1397–1459":"1397–1459","1440":"1440","July 1459":"heinäkuu 1459","1483":"1483","1459":"1459","Jul. 1459":"heinäkuu 1459","1502":"1502","1435":"1435","abt 1435":"noin 1435","1478":"1478","1379":"1379","1488":"1488","about 1435":"noin 1435","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","1441":"1441","about 1442":"noin 1442","about 1440":"noin 1440","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Closeburn, Dumfries-shire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Closeburn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Carnwath, 